[[File:Martin Brimmer by Sarah Wyman Whitman.jpg|thumb|Martin Brimmer, portrait by [[Sarah W. Whitman|Sarah Wyman Whitman]]]] '''Martin Brimmer''' (1829-January 14, 1896)<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary Record: Martin Brimmer|last=|first=|date=17 January 1896|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|work=|via=}}</ref> was an American politician and first president of the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arthistorians.info/brimmerm|title=Dictionary of Art Historians|website=arthistorians.info/|access-date=2017-02-22}}</ref>
Brimmer was the son of [[Martin Brimmer]], [[Mayor of Boston]]. He started his studies at Harvard University and graduated in 1849. He was a member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] from 1859-1861 and the [[Massachusetts Senate|Massachusetts State Senate]] in 1864. He was a [[Electoral College (United States)|presidential elector]] in the [[United States presidential election, 1876|US election of 1876]]. He also served on the Citizens' Relief Committee following the [[Great Boston fire of 1872]].<ref name=":0" />
