{{about|the Internet company|other uses|niche (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox company | name = Niche.com, Inc. | logo = Niche (Company) Logo.png | logo_size = 250px | type = [[Private company|Private]] | foundation = August 9, 2002 in [[Pittsburgh]] | key_people = Luke Skurman, Founder and CEO | former_name = College Prowler, Inc. | location_city = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania|PA]] | location_country = [[United States]] | num_employees = 45 | homepage = [https://www.niche.com/ www.niche.com] }}
'''Niche.com, Inc.''', formerly known as '''College Prowler''',<ref name="rebrand1">{{citation|title=A website for rating 'big life decisions'|date=October 10, 2013|first=Eli|last=Epstein|url=http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/10/10/a-website-for-rating-big-life-decisions/|publisher=[[CNN.com|CNN]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426215253/http://tech.fortune.cnn.com/2013/10/10/a-website-for-rating-big-life-decisions/|archivedate=April 26, 2014|df=}}</ref><ref name="rebrand2">{{citation|title=College Prowler becomes Niche and wants to help you make big decisions|date=October 11, 2013|first=Malia|last=Spencer|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/blog/techflash/2013/10/college-prowler-becomes-niche-and.html?page=all|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Business Times]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516072330/http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/blog/techflash/2013/10/college-prowler-becomes-niche-and.html?page=all|archivedate=May 16, 2014|df=}}</ref> is an American company headquartered in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], that runs a [[ranking]] and [[review site]].<ref name="rebrand2" /> The company was founded by Luke Skurman in 2002 as a [[Publishing|publisher]] of print guidebooks on [[United States|US]] [[college]]s, but now runs a website with information on [[K–12 (education)|K-12 schools]], [[college]]s, [[City|cities]], [[Neighbourhood|neighborhoods]], and companies across the United States and Puerto Rico.<ref name="rebrand1" /><ref name="Inc">{{citation|title=Case Study: Finding the Right Price for a Hot Product|date=October 1, 2009|first=Donna|last=Fenn|url=http://www.inc.com/magazine/20091001/finding-the-right-price-for-a-hot-product.html|publisher=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc. Magazine]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref>
==History== Niche was founded as College Prowler in August 2002 by Luke Skurman.<ref name="Inc" /> Then a student at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]'s [[Tepper School of Business]], Skurman spun the company out of a project in his [[entrepreneurship]] class.<ref name="Inc" />
In 2004, the small company obtained an investment of $500,000 from [[Glen Meakem]], who became the Chairman.<ref>{{citation|title=Review, rankings site College Prowler joins Niche group|date=October 4, 2014|first=Deborah|last=Todd|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/businessnews/2013/10/04/Review-rankings-site-College-Prowler-joins-Niche-group/stories/201310040092page=all|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=October 17, 2018|deadurl=no}}</ref> In 2005, College Prowler was recognized by [[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] for being one of the 50 fastest-growing companies in the nation.<ref>{{citation|title=2005 Fast 50 Winner|date=March 1, 2005|first=|last=|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1172796/most-innovative-companies-2005/27luke-skurman|publisher=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929002216/http://www.fastcompany.com/1172796/most-innovative-companies-2005/27luke-skurman|archivedate=September 29, 2014|df=}}</ref> Originally, the company produced print guidebooks, but by 2007 their content was made available online for a [[Subscription business model|subscription fee]], and then by 2009 the subscription was removed making all [[web content]] free.<ref name="Inc" /><ref>{{citation|title=College Prowler soars after making switch to business model|date=August 12, 2011|first=Malia|last=Spencer|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/print-edition/2011/08/12/college-prowler-soars-business-model.html?page=all|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Business Times]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516072332/http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/print-edition/2011/08/12/college-prowler-soars-business-model.html?page=all|archivedate=May 16, 2014|df=}}</ref>
==Product== Niche, as College Prowler, provided rankings, report cards (with attributed grades) and reviews of colleges in the US.<ref name="rebrand3">{{citation|title=Review, rankings site College Prowler becomes Niche|date=October 4, 2013|first=Deborah|last=Todd|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/businessnews/2013/10/04/Review-rankings-site-College-Prowler-joins-Niche-group/stories/201310040092|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426202125/http://www.post-gazette.com/business/businessnews/2013/10/04/Review-rankings-site-College-Prowler-joins-Niche-group/stories/201310040092|archivedate=April 26, 2014|df=}}</ref> During their rebranding process, in addition to colleges, Niche added coverage of K-12 schools as well as neighborhoods under their "places to live" category.<ref name="rebrand1" /><ref name="forbes">{{citation|title=Best cities and neighborhoods for millenials|date=April 14, 2014|first=Kathryn|last=Dill|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kathryndill/2014/04/14/1916/|publisher=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422011204/http://www.forbes.com/sites/kathryndill/2014/04/14/1916/|archivedate=April 22, 2014|df=}}</ref>
==Criticism== In a 2008 scandal known as "Facebookgate",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/campus-overload/2010/02/_admissions_officers_a_bit.html|title=Campus Overload - Facebookgate, the 2010 edition|author=|date=|website=washingtonpost.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://higheredlive.com/episode-14-facebookgate-three-years-of-facebook-forgery/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429051751/http://higheredlive.com/episode-14-facebookgate-three-years-of-facebook-forgery/ |archivedate=2014-04-29 |df= }} Facebookgate: Three Years of Facebook Forgery</ref> hundreds of spurious "Class of 2013" groups were created on [[Facebook]] for the purpose of promoting College Prowler.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://targetx.com/xperttip-no-89-facebookgate-summary-of-a-scandal/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429045311/http://targetx.com/xperttip-no-89-facebookgate-summary-of-a-scandal/ |archivedate=2014-04-29 |df= }} Facebookgate: Summary of a Scandal</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://andrewcareaga.wordpress.com/2008/12/19/facebookgate/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140429080340/http://andrewcareaga.wordpress.com/2008/12/19/facebookgate/ |archivedate=2014-04-29 |df= }} Facebookgate - Higher Ed Marketing</ref> Such groups would normally be created by actual students or colleges themselves. According to the CEO, "The original purpose was to use these groups as a way to inform students that they can access a free guide about their new college on our site." He also added, "No employee or anyone else associated with College Prowler has used these groups to send out messages or wall posts."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Company-Created/42157/|title=Company Created Official-Looking 'Class of 2013' Facebook Groups for Hundreds of Colleges|author=|date=19 December 2008|website=chronicle.com|accessdate=1 May 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174411/https://www.chronicle.com/article/Company-Created/42157|archivedate=10 January 2018|df=}}</ref> College Prowler later removed all administrative access from the 125 groups, admitting "It was clearly over the line".
